<link href="adcp.css" rel="stylesheet"><entry><xh5>blow it • blow me</xh5><p> <i>blow it—</i>1. <i>(sl.)</i> lose or bungle an opportunity, etc.: He’ll probably <u>blow it</u>. He’s beginning to look old. 2. (<i>interj.)</i> used as an oath or expletive to express annoyance: <u>Blow it</u>! I just can’t get this wallpaper straight!</p><p> <div class="note">Note</div> The expression does not correlate in meaning with the phrase <b>blow it out of proportion</b>—make smth. appear more significant than it should be: It’s sensational and it is easy to make headlines out of it. But the media <u>blew it out of proportion</u>. </p><p><i>blow me—</i>1. <i>(UK)</i> is used as an emphatic exclamation to express surprise <i>(also: blow me down): </i><u>Blow me</u> if it isn’t old Charley—I’ve not seen you for years: how are you, old friend? 2. <i>(U.S. coarse sl.)</i> a very vulgar phrase with sexual implication hurled by an angry person: And if the authorities don’t like it—well, they can <u>blow me</u>! </p> </entry>
